<DOC><DOCNO> AP880915-0221 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0027EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   09-15 0550</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0574</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House has moved toward tougher treatmentfor Wall Street insider traders, passing legislation that woulddramatically increase their fines and prison terms and penalizeinvestment firms where the practice takes place.   The measure was passed Wednesday. Its fate is unclear in theSenate, where the legislation may not advance unless the Houseapproves a Senate-passed banking bill.</TEXT><DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Playtex Holdings Inc. says it will splitinto two separate companies under a series of buyout transactionstotaling about $1.3 billion, led by a group headed by Chairman JoelE. Smilow.   The deal announced Wednesday would separate Playtex' familyproducts businesses from its intimate apparel operations.   The group led by Smilow, members of Playtex Holdings managementand Thomas H. Lee Co., a Boston-based investment firm, agreed topay cash and securities valued at about $530 million for thecompany's privately-held common shares.   The group also will acquire or redeem Playtex Holdings'outstanding debt and preferred stock worth $770 million.   A second group, led by Smilow and members of Playtex ApparelProducts Inc. management, then would acquire that business for $380million in cash.</TEXT><DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Harvard University says it is raising$30 million to start companies to commercialize medical research, amove academics believe creates potential conflicts between thepursuits of knowledge and profit.   Wednesday's decision comes eight years after Harvard scrapped aplan amid controversy to invest in a professor's geneticengineering work after the university's involvement in business wasdeemed unethical.   Administrators said the new scheme would raise money needed tosupplement Harvard Medical School's $350 million research budget.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal judge upheld the partial merger ofthe Detroit Free Press and Detroit News under a joint operatingagreement approved last month by then-Attorney General Edwin MeeseIII.   U.S. District Judge George Revercomb on Wednesday rejectedcontentions by a group of Detroit advertisers and readers that themorning Free Press, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., was not a failingnewspaper entitled to antitrust exemptions.   The judge said he would allow a month-old court ordertemporarily blocking the deal to expire at 7:15 p.m. on Saturday _a delay that could give opponents time to appeal the ruling to afederal appeals court.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The five airline-owned computer reservationsystems used by travel agents to book passengers are so dominantthat they are stifling competition in the air travel industry, acongressional report says.   The study released Wednesday concluded the reservation systemsare generating profits ``exceeding those that could reasonably beexpected to be earned in a competitive market.''   It also chided the Department of Transportation for failing totake steps to eliminate ``anti-competitive features'' of thecomputer reservation industry.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market hit a five-week high Wednesday, responding tobetter-than-expected news on U.S. trade. The Dow Jones average of30 industrials climbed 17.60 points to 2,100.64.   The dollar rose after the government announced the sharpest U.S.trade-deficit drop in nearly six years. Gold prices declinedmarginally in late U.S. trading.   Bond prices rose.   Speculation about Hurricane Gilbert swept through the nation'scommodity exchanges, fanning increases in cotton, oil, grain andsilver futures prices while helping to limit gains in the cattlemarket.</TEXT></DOC>